ularity -- tIV. Ancient Grammar in Historical Context -- tNew Papyri and the History of Ancient Grammar: The έπίρρημα Chapter in P. Berol. 9917 -- tQuintilian’s ‘Grammar’ (Inst.1.4-8) and its Importance for the History of Roman Grammar -- tSyntax before Syntax: Uses of the Term σύνταξις in Greek Grammarians before Apollonius Dyscolus -- tSyntagms in the Artigraphic Latin Grammars -- tLatin Grammatical Manuals in the Early Middle Ages: Tradition and Adaptation in the Participle Chapter -- tTheodosius and his Byzantine Successors on the Participle: A Didactic Approach -- tThe Orus Fragments in the Ethnica of Stephanus of Byzantium -- tV. Ancient Grammar in Interdisciplinary Context -- tDionysius of Halicarnassus and the Scholia on Thucydides’ Syntax -- tImposition of Names in Ancient Grammar and Philosophy -- tNeoplatonic Commentators on Aristotle: The ‘Arbitrariness of the Linguistic Sign’ -- tList of Contributors -- tAbbreviations -- tBibliography -- tGeneral Index -- tPassages Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAncient Greek scholarship is currently in the centre of a multi-faceted and steadily growing research activity. The volume aims at investigating archetypes, concepts and contexts of the ancient philological discipline from a historical, methodological and ideological perspective. It includes 26 contributions by leading scholars divided into four sections: The ancient scholars at work, The ancient grammarians on Greek language and linguistic correctness, Ancient grammar in historical context and Ancient grammar in interdisciplinary context. The period examined coincides with the establishment of scholarship as an autonomous discipline from the 3rd century BC to its peak in the first centuries AD. Archetypes and paradigms of philological activity during the classical era help investigate the origins of ancient scholarship, and the interdisciplinary discourse between scholarship, philosophy of language and rhetoric is illustrated. Thus, the thematic spectrum of the volume stretches from the 4th century BC to the Byzantine era. Apart from the Greek antiquity, central aspects of the Latin grammatical tradition are also being examined.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aGreek languagexGrammar, Historical. 4aGrammatik. 4aLinguistik. 4aSprache. 4aSprachwissenschaft in der Antike. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAncient Scholarship.  aGrammar.  aLanguage.  aLinguistics.1 aAx, Wolfram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasset, Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBillerbeck, Margarethe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBing, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonnet, Guillaume, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraswell, Bruce Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChriti, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChronopoulos, Stelios, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElst, Valerie van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFantuzzi, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunter, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLallot, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, Frédéric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuhtala, Anneli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLundon, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthaios, Stephano